fields.description:
To make content widget configuration more flexible, and avoid having to create a large number of widgets with static configurations, we are starting to support content configuration placeholders. Placeholders can have a substantial impact on performance and hardware requirements, so we will introduce support for specific fields over time in a controlled fashion to avoid operational issues. 

Initially, we want to support the ability to submit key-values from a content widget tag to be replaced in the content configuration "query" and "filter" fields.

A placeholder has the general syntax:	
{code}
{<source>:<key>|<default>}
{code}

* The <source> field defines where <key> comes from. Initially, we will support "parameter" (values coming from the widget tag). Later, we will introduce “content” for values from the content profile, “user” for values from the user profile, and “event” for value from the current event, but this is not part of this ticket.
* The <key> field defines the key we use for the replacement, i.e., the placeholder is replaced with the value associated with <key>.
* The symbols {noformat} { } : | {noformat} cannot appear in <source>, <key> or <default>.
* The <default> value kicks in if the <source>:<key> for some reason is invalid or otherwise cannot be evaluated.
* There can be multiple placeholders in the same query or filter field

Example: 
{code}
"filter": "filter(category:\"{parameter:productcategory|electronics}\")"
"query": "query(title:\"{parameter:userquery|*}\")"
{code}

These placeholders will be supported for the type "recs" with matching modes: "trend", "contextual", "behavioral", "collabctx", "collabusr", and "explicit"

The placeholder key-values are submitted from the widget tag using the context object, see example below:

{code}
{ context: { parameters: { category:'cameras', userquery:'sony' } } }
{code}

To enable a good base for performance and audience reporting and segment creation, we want to track impressions and click events for the individual recommendations with associated meta information.

For content configuration types "recs" and "fixed", it will be possible to define a reporting object (a list of key-value pairs) that will end up as customer parameters with the DMP impression or click event that is sent for each individual recommended item.

Example:
{code}
"reporting": [ {"key" : "segment" , "value" : "32gfdeyt244r"}, { "key" : "mode", "value" : "contextual"} , { "key" : "scenario", "value" : "subscribers" }  ]
{code}

The reporting object will also support placeholder parameters from the widget tag:

{code}
"reporting": [ {"key" : "category" , "value" : "{parameter:productcategory|none}" },  {"key" : "product", "value" : "{parameter:id|0}" }  ]
{code}

We want to introduce the ability to perform impression capping making sure that a user isn't exposed to the same message/experience/output more than a preconfigured number of times.

The configuration will be based on using conditions with the following syntax:

{code}
            {
              "type": "recs",
              "condition": {
                "type": "impressionCapping", "count": 8, "period": 86400, "capTag" : "subscriptionpromotion"}
                [...]
              },
              "matchingMode": {...}
              },
            }
{code}

- We introduce a new condition type "impressionCapping".
- The "count" and "period" fields are used to restrict the exposure of results. An individual user can only be exposed to results up to and including the value of "count" during the "period".
- The "period" is measured in seconds, and the max value for period is 604800, corresponding to 7 days.
- The field "capTag" acts as a label for the impression capping. This allows multiple branches to define impression capping tracked towards the same label.

Tracking of impressions must capture the combination of the user id, the time, and the "capTag". The impression tracking count is increased with the number of items returned.

An impression is not counted if:
- The branch returns no results
- The branch returns backfill

h3. Suggested solution:

The customer can provide a query string as a parameter. For terms in this string that are not present in the body field of the indexes being searched, provide suggestions for similar terms that exist in the body field of the indexes.

h3. Example:
{code}
$ cx.py /document/search '{"siteId":"1234567489","spellcheck":{"query":"cxence insigh"}}'
{
  "totalCount": 0,
  "matches": [],
  "spellcheck": [
    {
      "term": "cxence",
      "suggetions": [
        {
          "term": "cxense"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "term": "insigh",
      "suggetions": [
        {
          "term": "insight"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
{code}

h3. Original description:
Customer:   Deseret Digital Media
[Support Ticket  10510 | https://emediate1.zendesk.com/agent/tickets/10510]

Deseret Digital Media is testing a migration to the new search API, and are not happy to see that the Did-You-Mean / Spellcheck dictionaries are removed when we went from legacy search to new search API.   It would be a great feature to add to prove that we are committed to continuous improvements in the service accessible through the new search API.

Deseret Digital Media is seeing that they have some zero hit queries related to misspellings, and would like to automatically correct spelling of certain query terms that come out with zero hits.  The customer is referring to this feature as "misspellings (slop scores)".

The current "Explicit" mode supports some search driven recommendation scenarios, but lack flexibility. We want to introduce a new Search matching mode that allows a user to define an advanced search query, including support for sorting. With placeholders, it will also be possible to inject a user query from a search box.

After the introduction of the "Search" mode, the "Explicit" mode can be deprecated.

The Search mode can be configured as follows:

{code}
{
  "type": "recs",
  "siteIds": [
    "12345"
  ],
  "matchingMode": {
    “search": {      
      "weight": 1,   
      "sort”: [..], 
    }
  }
}
{code}

The fields "query", "filter", and "sort" will support placeholders.

Support for the following fields from document/search is not within scope for this ticket:
- facets 
- start
- highlights
- logQuery (covered by "reporting" with placeholder)

In particular, facets is essential for commerce search, and will be addressed in a separate ticket.

Current content recommendation algorithms only leverage page view data. By supporting recommendations based on performance events (actions), we open up to support a wide range of useful and precise recommendation scenarios. These include common collaborative filtering scenarios that are important for video, retail, and marketing use cases.

See below for example configurations. 

- The source event and destination event are DMP event types. 
- The source and destination filters are operating on the customer parameters of the DMP event. Multiple filters are treated as AND.
- The "identityparameter" field defines the DMP event custom parameter that represents the ID of the document
- The "identityfield" field defines which document field matches the "identity" values from the DMP event

The source and destination filter fields need to support placeholders.

Example 1 - People who viewed (where view is a DMP event type) product with ID 26554634, ended up buying these products from category cameras:

{code}
{
  "type": "recs",
  "siteIds": [
    "12345"
  ],
  "matchingMode": {
    "actions": {      
      "weight": 1,
      "sourceevent" : "view",
      "sourcefilter" : [ "sku" : "26554634" ],
      "destinationevent" : "buy",
      "destinationfilter" : [ "category" : "cameras" ],
      "identityparameter" : "sku",
      "identityfield" : "articleid",
      "period" : 86400
    }
  }
}
{code}

Example 2 - People who bought a Samsung camera ended up buying these lenses:

{code}
{
  "type": "recs",
  "siteIds": [
    "12345"
  ],
  "matchingMode": {
    "actions": {      
      "weight": 1,
      "sourceevent" : "buy",
      "sourcefilter" : [ "category" : "cameras", "brand" : "samsung" ],
      "destinationevent" : "buy",
      "destinationfilter" : [ "category" : "lenses" ],
      "identityparameter" : "sku",
      "identityfield" : "articleid",
      "period" : 86400
    }
  }
}
{code}

Example 3 - Top sellers from the tablet category:

{code}
{
  "type": "recs",
  "siteIds": [
    "12345"
  ],
  "matchingMode": {
    "actions": {      
      "weight": 1,
      "destinationevent" : "buy",
      "destinationfilter" : [ "category" : "tablet" ],
      "identityparameter" : "sku",
      "identityfield" : "articleid",
      "period" : 86400
    }
  }
}
{code}

Example 4 - Top videos started from in the sports category:

{code}
{
  "type": "recs",
  "siteIds": [
    "12345"
  ],
  "matchingMode": {
    "actions": {      
      "weight": 1,
      "destinationevent" : "streamStart",
      "destinationfilter" : [ "category" : "sports" ],
      "identityparameter" : "guid",
      "identityfield" : "cxd-guid",
      "period" : 86400
    }
  }
}
{code}

Example 5 - People who watched more than half of this video also watched these videos:

{code}
{
  "type": "recs",
  "siteIds": [
    "12345"
  ],
  "matchingMode": {
    "actions": {      
      "weight": 1,
      "sourceevent" : "percentComplete",
      "sourcefilter" : [ "guid" : "4c553c39-cc36-4408-a872-7c0f3d990ccc", "percent" : "50" ],
      "destinationevent" : "streamStart",
      "identityparameter" : "guid",
      "identityfield" : "cxd-guid",
      "period" : 86400
    }
  }
}
{code}

A new “recent” matching mode should be introduced. The overall purpose of this new mode is to be able to easily provide a widget that displays the current user’s most recent activity sorted chronologically. In most cases, you would not want duplicate items to be shown. Assume that this is best solved wrapping the mode in "uniquified", rather than providing explicit configuration of duplicates in the "recent" mode.

We need to support the "recent" mode based on both page views and DMP events. It must be possible to filter the content, for instance displaying recently viewed products within the camera category.

Below are two configuration examples that shows the available configuration fields for page view events and DMP events separately.

Recent documents based on a page views (for example recently read articles):

{code}
{
  "type": "recs",
  "siteIds": [
    "12345"
  ],
  "matchingMode": {
    "recent": {      
      "weight": 1, 
      "mode" : "pageview"  
    }
  }
}
{code}

Recent documents based on a particular action (for example recently bought products):

{code}
{
  "type": "recs",
  "siteIds": [
    "12345"
  ],
  "matchingMode": {
    "recent": {      
      "weight": 1, 
      "mode" : "dmp",
      "event" : "buy"
    }
  }
}
{code}
